{"title_page": "Raman Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = The former Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh, Dr. Raman Singh.jpg\n| name = Raman Singh\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|10|15|df=y}}<ref name=Biodata/>\n| birth_place = [[Kawardha]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] (now in [[Chhattisgarh]]), India\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = 2nd [[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]]\n| successor = [[Bhupesh Baghel]]\n| predecessor = [[Ajit Jogi]]\n| term_start = 7 December 2003\n| term_end = 16 December 2018\n| office1 = [[Member of Legislative Assembly|Member]] of [[Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly]]\n| successor1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Uday Mudliyar]]\n| constituency1 = [[Rajnandgaon (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]]\n| term_start1 = [[2008 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|7 December 2008]]\n| term_end1 = \n| successor2 = Kheduram Sahu\n| predecessor2 = [[Pradeep Gandhi]]\n| constituency2 = Dongargaon\n| term_start2 = January 2004\n| term_end2 = 7 December 2008\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Commerce and Industry (India)|Minister of State for Commerce and Industry]]\n| term_start3 = 13 December 1999\n| term_end3 = 29 January 2003\n| office4= [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start4     = 1999\n| term_end4      = 2003\n| predecessor4  = [[Motilal Vora]] \n| successor4 = [[Pradeep Gandhi]]\n| constituency4 = [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Legislative Assembly]], [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Madhya Pradesh]]\n| constituency5 = [[Kawardha]]\n| successor5 = [[Yogeshwar Raj Singh]]\n| predecessor5 = Rani Shashi Prabha Devi\n| term_start5 = [[1990 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|1990]]\n| term_end5 = [[1998 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|1998]]\n| office6 = National Vice President, [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n     Incumbent\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] \n| spouse = Veena Singh\n| children = 2; including [[Abhishek Singh (politician)|Abhishek Singh]]\n}}\n'''Raman Singh''' (born 15 October 1952) is an Indian politician who was the 2nd [[Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]] from 7 December 2003 to 16 December 2018. He is the National Vice-President of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. He is also an [[Ayurveda|ayurvedic]] practitioner. He is also the longest serving [[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|CM]] of Chhattisgarh for 15 years.\n\n==Background==\nRaman Singh was born in [[Kawardha]] to Vighnaharan Singh Thakur, an [[advocate]], and Sudha Singh. After completion of schooling, he graduated from Government Science College, Bemetara in 1972. He also studied [[Ayurvedic Medicine]] at Government Ayurvedic College, [[Raipur]].<ref name=\"Raman Singh Biography - About family, political life, awards won, history\">{{cite web |title=Raman Singh Biography - About family, political life, awards won, history |publisher=Elections.in|date=10 November 2018 |url=http://www.elections.in/political-leaders/raman-singh.html |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nSingh joined the [[Bharatiya Jan Sangh]] as a youth member and was the president of youth wing in [[Kawardha]] in 1976-77. He progressed to become a councillor of Kawardha municipality in 1983.<ref name=Biodata/>\n\nHe was elected to [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] consecutively in 1990 and 1993. In 1999 he was elected to the [[13th Lok Sabha]] from the [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]] constituency in Chhattisgarh. In the government of [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], Singh became the Union Minister of State for Commerce and Industry from 1999 to 2003. He was later named as President of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) in the new state of Chhattisgarh, and led the party to a victory in the [[State Assembly elections in India, 2003|2003 state Assembly elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/12/06/stories/2003120606210100.htm | title=Governor invites Raman Singh | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=6 December 2003 | accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> With the other main contender for the Chief Minister's post, [[Dilip Singh Judeo]], caught in the midst of a scam, the BJP leadership named Raman Singh as Chhattisgarh's second Chief Minister, and the first person to be elected to that post.<ref name=Zeenews>{{cite news |url=http://www.zeenews.com/Elections08/chattisgarhstory.aspx?aid=482905 |publisher=Zee News |title=Chhattisgarh: CMs in the wings |first=Devika |last=Chhibber |accessdate=10 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412064718/http://www.zeenews.com/Elections08/chattisgarhstory.aspx?aid=482905 |archivedate=12 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has received praise for his organisational abilities, as reflected in his state's position with regard to implementation of a programme to improve the conditions of [[Scheduled Tribes]] and [[Scheduled Castes]]. The [[United Nations]] has also recognised the work done in Chhattisgarh under his leadership and the fiscal management of the state is another aspect for which he is known.<ref name=Zeenews />\n\nHe banned [[naxalite]] organisations in Chhattisgarh in 2002 under the \"[[Salwa Judum]]\" initiative, a move supported by the opposition party as well, led by [[Mahendra Karma]] who was assassinated by naxalites on 25 May 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-to-train-its-guns-on-raman-singh/article4760430.ece | title=Congress to train its guns on Raman Singh | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=29 May 2013 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Gupta, Smita}}</ref>  Singh was sworn in for his second term on 12 December 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/mr-clean-raman-singh-helped-bjp-keep-chhattisgarh/80080-30.html |title=CHHATTISGARH: Raman's clean image helped BJP |publisher=[[IBN Live]] |accessdate= 10 November 2013 }}</ref> On 8 December 2013 he was re-elected as the chief minister (CM) of the state.\n\nHe [[2013 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|won re-election in 2013]] for his third tenure as a CM of Chhattisgarh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/a-record-7465-polling-in-chhattisgarh-phaseii/article5367110.ece|title=A record 74.65% polling in Chhattisgarh phase-II|first=Suvojit|last=Bagchi|date=19 November 2013|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> After the loss of his party in the 2018 assembly elections, he resigned as the CM of Chhattisgarh on 11 December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/story/chhattisgarh-cm-raman-singh-resigns-takes-responsibility-1407284-2018-12-11|title=Raman Singh resigns as Chhattisgarh CM, takes moral responsibility for loss|last=RaipurDecember 11|first=IndiaToday in|last2=December 11|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11|last3=Ist|first3=2018 18:50}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2013, Former Chief Minister Raman Singh, members of his cabinet and others have been accused of corruption over the alleged scam in Chhattisgarh Civil Supplies Corporation 'Naan'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrika.com/raipur-news/nan-scam-chhattisgarh-main-accuse-raised-allegation-on-raman-singh-5087803|title=The then Chief Minister, Dr. Raman Singh was the main mastermind of the 36 thousand crore Naan scam|last=13 Sep 2019, 10:06 PM IST|first=Patrika}}</ref>\nShiv Shankar Bhatt, the main accused in the state's famous Naan scam case, said that in 2013, 21 lakh fake ration cards were produced under pressure from the then CM Raman Singh and Food Minister. This caused a loss of about 3 thousand crores to the government every year. According to the source, it is also claimed that the BJP fought the 2013 assembly election from the scam money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhattisgarh/raipur/news/chief-accused-of-naan-scam-said-21-lakh-fake-ration-cards-made-under-pressure-of-former-c-01641071.html|title=21 lakh fake ration cards made under the pressure of former CM Raman Singh|last=Sep 14, 2019|first= 10:09 AM IST Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2017, his son [[Abhishek Singh]]'s name appeared in the famous \"[[Panama Papers]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lSbRp48jtLs|title=Chhattisgarh CM Raman Singh in trouble along with his son Abhishek Singh|last=Aug 4, 2017|first=ABP News Youtube}}</ref> While rejecting the allegations against him, Abhishek had said at the time that the topics being raised related to his so-called foreign account are completely untrue and politically motivated. He said that a conspiracy is being hatched against him. Later as per the news articles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/bjp-mp-chhattisgarh-cm-raman-singh-son-is-man-named-in-offshore-accounts-leak-congress-5250351/|title=BJP MP, Chhattisgarh CM\u2019s son is man named in offshore accounts leak|last=July 8, 2018|first=1:09:40 pm The Indian Express}}</ref> it was found that in all the papers Abhishek Singh clarified that he only is Abhishak Singh.\n\nIn 2017, The [[Supreme Court of India]] had ordered the [[Chhattisgarh]] government to submit the original file related to the purchase of [[AgustaWestland]] helicopters in 2006. The then Chhattisgarh government issued a global tender \"suspiciously\" to buy a helicopter and paid \"over 30 per cent\" without looking for any other option.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/chhattisgarh/supreme-court-asks-chhattisgarh-government-to-produce-original-files-of-augusta-westland-deal|title=Raman government's problems may increase in AgustaWestland helicopter case|last=16 Nov 2017|first=5:21 PM IST Amar Ujala}}</ref>\nRaman Singh's son Abhishek Singh was also accused of taking money through companies opened in the [[British Virgin Islands]]. However, Raman Singh has termed all these allegations as baseless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/story/supreme-court-raman-singh-son-abhishek-singh-agusta-westland-helicopter-petition-1-983788.html}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the police, Singh's son-in-law Puneet Gupta is accused of committing alleged financial irregularities of Rs 50 crore while holding the post of Superintendent of Government DKS Hospital, Raipur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/former-chhattisgarh-cm-raman-singh-s-son-in-law-booked-for-rs-50-crore-fraud-1479270-2019-03-15|title=Former Chhattisgarh CM Raman Singh's son-in-law booked for Rs 50 crore fraud|last=March 15, 2019|first=UPDATED: 23:48 IST India Today}}</ref>\nHe is currently being investigated upon where he was asked to come to the police station and give a statement initially, he went missing for a few weeks but then came to the police station and refused to answer any questions .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/chhattisgarh-ex-cm-s-son-in-law-quizzed-by-cops-over-alleged-financial-scam/story-BTNH9wzryx3IJSMBC0yFrJ.html|title=Chhattisgarh ex-CM\u2019s son-in-law quizzed by cops over alleged financial scam|last=May 06, 2019|first= 23:31 IST Hindustan Times}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, a tape revealing the purchasing of  the candidates appeared in the local media. Since then, it is known as Antagarh tape kand(scandal), which included the names of many people including Raman Singh, [[Ajit Jogi]], [[Amit Jogi]]. At the same time there was a transaction of heavy money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhattisgarh/raipur/news/antagarh-tape-scandal-accused-former-mla-manturam-pawar-reached-sit-office-to-give-voice-sample-126199723.html|title=\u0905\u0902\u0924\u093e\u0917\u0922\u093c \u091f\u0947\u092a\u0915\u093e\u0902\u0921|last=Dec 03, 2019|first=03:02 PM IST Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>\n\nBesides this, there have also been allegations of multiple cases of corruption on the active minister. This includes being a party to priyadarshini bank scam where one of the accused has said his name in the narco test.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagran.com/news/national-chhattisgarh-congress-rakes-up-cooperative-bank-scam-10582243.html|title=Raman Singh and four ministers accused of taking bribe|last=21 Jul 2013|first=11:18 AM (IST)}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Biodata>{{cite web | url=http://dprcg.gov.in/sites/default/files/page-documents/BIO-DATA%20OF%20%20Dr.%20Raman%20Singh.pdf | title=Biodata: Dr. Raman Singh | publisher=[[Government of Chhattisgarh]] |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Motilal Vora]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]] |years=1999 \u2013 2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pradeep Gandhi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ajit Jogi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]]|years=7 December 2003 \u2013 16 December 2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bhupesh Baghel]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.drramansingh.in Official website]\n* [http://cgvidhansabha.gov.in/english/cm.htm Chhattisgarh Chief Minister Profile]\n* [http://egov.eletsonline.com/2018/04/progressive-chhattisgarh-reaching-new-milestones/ Progressive Chhattisgarh Reaching New Milestones]\n\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party chief ministers |state=collapsed}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Raman}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 1990\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 1993\u20131998]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh MLAs 2000\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh MLAs 2008\u20132013]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh MLAs 2003\u20132008]]\n[[Category:13th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:People from Kabirdham district]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh MLAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh members]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Chhattisgarh]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = The former Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh, Dr. Raman Singh.jpg\n| name = Raman Singh\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|10|15|df=y}}<ref name=Biodata/>\n| birth_place = [[Kawardha]], [[Madhya Pradesh]] (now in [[Chhattisgarh]]), India\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| office = 2nd [[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]]\n| successor = [[Bhupesh Baghel]]\n| predecessor = [[Ajit Jogi]]\n| term_start = 7 December 2003\n| term_end = 16 December 2018\n| office1 = [[Member of Legislative Assembly|Member]] of [[Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly]]\n| successor1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Uday Mudliyar]]\n| constituency1 = [[Rajnandgaon (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]]\n| term_start1 = [[2008 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|7 December 2008]]\n| term_end1 = \n| successor2 = Kheduram Sahu\n| predecessor2 = [[Pradeep Gandhi]]\n| constituency2 = Dongargaon\n| term_start2 = January 2004\n| term_end2 = 7 December 2008\n| office3 = [[Ministry of Commerce and Industry (India)|Minister of State for Commerce and Industry]]\n| term_start3 = 13 December 1999\n| term_end3 = 29 January 2003\n| office4= [[Member of Parliament]], [[Lok Sabha]]\n| term_start4     = 1999\n| term_end4      = 2003\n| predecessor4  = [[Motilal Vora]] \n| successor4 = [[Pradeep Gandhi]]\n| constituency4 = [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Legislative Assembly]], [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly|Madhya Pradesh]]\n| constituency5 = [[Kawardha]]\n| successor5 = [[Yogeshwar Raj Singh]]\n| predecessor5 = Rani Shashi Prabha Devi\n| term_start5 = [[1990 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|1990]]\n| term_end5 = [[1998 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|1998]]\n| office6 = National Vice President, [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n     Incumbent\n| party = [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] \n| spouse = Veena Singh\n| children = 2; including [[Abhishek Singh (politician)|Abhishek Singh]]\n}}\n'''Raman Singh''' (born 15 October 1952) is an Indian politician who was the 2nd [[Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]] from 7 December 2003 to 16 December 2018. He is the National Vice-President of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]]. He is also an [[Ayurveda|ayurvedic]] practitioner. He is also the longest serving [[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|CM]] of Chhattisgarh for 15 years.\n\n==Background==\nRaman Singh was born in [[Kawardha]] to Vighnaharan Singh Thakur, an [[advocate]], and Sudha Singh. After completion of schooling, he graduated from Government Science College, Bemetara in 1972. He also studied [[Ayurvedic Medicine]] at Government Ayurvedic College, [[Raipur]].<ref name=\"Raman Singh Biography - About family, political life, awards won, history\">{{cite web |title=Raman Singh Biography - About family, political life, awards won, history |publisher=Elections.in|date=10 November 2018 |url=http://www.elections.in/political-leaders/raman-singh.html |accessdate=17 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political career ==\nSingh joined the [[Bharatiya Jan Sangh]] as a youth member and was the president of youth wing in [[Kawardha]] in 1976-77. He progressed to become a councillor of Kawardha municipality in 1983.<ref name=Biodata/>\n\nHe was elected to [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]] consecutively in 1990 and 1993. In 1999 he was elected to the [[13th Lok Sabha]] from the [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]] constituency in Chhattisgarh. In the government of [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]], Singh became the Union Minister of State for Commerce and Industry from 1999 to 2003. He was later named as President of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) in the new state of Chhattisgarh, and led the party to a victory in the [[State Assembly elections in India, 2003|2003 state Assembly elections]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/12/06/stories/2003120606210100.htm | title=Governor invites Raman Singh | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=6 December 2003 | accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref> With the other main contender for the Chief Minister's post, [[Dilip Singh Judeo]], caught in the midst of a scam, the BJP leadership named Raman Singh as Chhattisgarh's second Chief Minister, and the first person to be elected to that post.<ref name=Zeenews>{{cite news |url=http://www.zeenews.com/Elections08/chattisgarhstory.aspx?aid=482905 |publisher=Zee News |title=Chhattisgarh: CMs in the wings |first=Devika |last=Chhibber |accessdate=10 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130412064718/http://www.zeenews.com/Elections08/chattisgarhstory.aspx?aid=482905 |archivedate=12 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe has received praise for his organisational abilities, as reflected in his state's position with regard to implementation of a programme to improve the conditions of [[Scheduled Tribes]] and [[Scheduled Castes]]. The [[United Nations]] has also recognised the work done in Chhattisgarh under his leadership and the fiscal management of the state is another aspect for which he is known.<ref name=Zeenews />\n\nHe banned [[naxalite]] organisations in Chhattisgarh in 2002 under the \"[[Salwa Judum]]\" initiative, a move supported by the opposition party as well, led by [[Mahendra Karma]] who was assassinated by naxalites on 25 May 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-to-train-its-guns-on-raman-singh/article4760430.ece | title=Congress to train its guns on Raman Singh | newspaper=[[The Hindu]] | date=29 May 2013 | accessdate=10 November 2013 | author=Gupta, Smita}}</ref>  Singh was sworn in for his second term on 12 December 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/mr-clean-raman-singh-helped-bjp-keep-chhattisgarh/80080-30.html |title=CHHATTISGARH: Raman's clean image helped BJP |publisher=[[IBN Live]] |accessdate= 10 November 2013 }}</ref> On 8 December 2013 he was re-elected as the chief minister (CM) of the state.\n\nHe [[2013 Chhattisgarh Legislative Assembly election|won re-election in 2013]] for his third tenure as a CM of Chhattisgarh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/a-record-7465-polling-in-chhattisgarh-phaseii/article5367110.ece|title=A record 74.65% polling in Chhattisgarh phase-II|first=Suvojit|last=Bagchi|date=19 November 2013|publisher=|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> After the loss of his party in the 2018 assembly elections, he resigned as the CM of Chhattisgarh on 11 December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/elections/story/chhattisgarh-cm-raman-singh-resigns-takes-responsibility-1407284-2018-12-11|title=Raman Singh resigns as Chhattisgarh CM, takes moral responsibility for loss|last=RaipurDecember 11|first=IndiaToday in|last2=December 11|first2=2018UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2018-12-11|last3=Ist|first3=2018 18:50}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 2013, Former Chief Minister Raman Singh, members of his cabinet and others have been accused of corruption over the alleged scam in Chhattisgarh Civil Supplies Corporation 'Naan'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrika.com/raipur-news/nan-scam-chhattisgarh-main-accuse-raised-allegation-on-raman-singh-5087803|title=The then Chief Minister, Dr. Raman Singh was the main mastermind of the 36 thousand crore Naan scam|last=13 Sep 2019, 10:06 PM IST|first=Patrika}}</ref>\nShiv Shankar Bhatt, the main accused in the state's famous Naan scam case, said that in 2013, 21 lakh fake ration cards were produced under pressure from the then CM Raman Singh and Food Minister. This caused a loss of about 3 thousand crores to the government every year. According to the source, it is also claimed that the BJP fought the 2013 assembly election from the scam money.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/chhattisgarh/raipur/news/chief-accused-of-naan-scam-said-21-lakh-fake-ration-cards-made-under-pressure-of-former-c-01641071.html|title=21 lakh fake ration cards made under the pressure of former CM Raman Singh|last=Sep 14, 2019|first= 10:09 AM IST Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>\n\nIn the year 2017, his son [[Abhishek Singh]]'s name appeared in the famous \"[[Panama Papers]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lSbRp48jtLs|title=Chhattisgarh CM Raman Singh in trouble along with his son Abhishek Singh|last=Aug 4, 2017|first=ABP News Youtube}}</ref> While rejecting the allegations against him, Abhishek had said at the time that the topics being raised related to his so-called foreign account are completely untrue and politically motivated. He said that a conspiracy is being hatched against him. Later as per the news articles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/bjp-mp-chhattisgarh-cm-raman-singh-son-is-man-named-in-offshore-accounts-leak-congress-5250351/|title=BJP MP, Chhattisgarh CM\u2019s son is man named in offshore accounts leak|last=July 8, 2018|first=1:09:40 pm The Indian Express}}</ref> it was found that in all the papers Abhishek Singh clarified that he only is Abhishak Singh.\n\nIn 2017, The [[Supreme Court of India]] had ordered the [[Chhattisgarh]] government to submit the original file related to the purchase of [[AgustaWestland]] helicopters in 2006. The then Chhattisgarh government issued a global tender \"suspiciously\" to buy a helicopter and paid \"over 30 per cent\" without looking for any other option.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amarujala.com/chhattisgarh/supreme-court-asks-chhattisgarh-government-to-produce-original-files-of-augusta-westland-deal|title=Raman government's problems may increase in AgustaWestland helicopter case|last=16 Nov 2017|first=5:21 PM IST Amar Ujala}}</ref>\nRaman Singh's son Abhishek Singh was also accused of taking money through companies opened in the [[British Virgin Islands]]. However, Raman Singh has termed all these allegations as baseless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aajtak.intoday.in/story/supreme-court-raman-singh-son-abhishek-singh-agusta-westland-helicopter-petition-1-983788.html|last=13 Feb 2018|first=12:11 IST Aaj Tak}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=Biodata>{{cite web | url=http://dprcg.gov.in/sites/default/files/page-documents/BIO-DATA%20OF%20%20Dr.%20Raman%20Singh.pdf | title=Biodata: Dr. Raman Singh | publisher=[[Government of Chhattisgarh]] |accessdate=10 November 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|in-lwr}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Motilal Vora]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[Rajnandgaon (Lok Sabha constituency)|Rajnandgaon]] |years=1999 \u2013 2003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pradeep Gandhi]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ajit Jogi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh|Chief Minister of Chhattisgarh]]|years=7 December 2003 \u2013 16 December 2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bhupesh Baghel]]}}\n|-\n{{s-end}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.drramansingh.in Official website]\n* [http://cgvidhansabha.gov.in/english/cm.htm Chhattisgarh Chief Minister Profile]\n* [http://egov.eletsonline.com/2018/04/progressive-chhattisgarh-reaching-new-milestones/ Progressive Chhattisgarh Reaching New Milestones]\n\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party chief ministers |state=collapsed}}\n{{Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Raman}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chief ministers from Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n[[Category:Chief Ministers of Chhattisgarh]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 1990\u20131992]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 1993\u20131998]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh MLAs 2000\u20132003]]\n[[Category:Chhattisgarh